ition phases and in parents' daily experiences of juggling work and family life. It highlights some difficult and complex issues about the sustainability of contemporary working practices for bringing up children that are highly relevant in times of economic retrenchment. 'Transitions to parenthood in Europe' will be of interest to an academic readership at all levels of the social sciences, as well as employers, managers, trade unions and policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aParentingvCross-cultural studieszEurope. 0aWork and familyvCross-cultural studieszEurope. 0aWork-life balancevCross-cultural studieszEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBrannen, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrannen, Julia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBäck-Wiklund, Margareta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDulk, Laura den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuerreiro, Maria das Dores, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovacheva, Siyka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Suzan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Suzan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNilsen, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNilsen, Ann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPeper, Bram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlantin, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmithson, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 avan Doorne-Huiskes, Anneke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id